t136.text: They should tell the somm or server what mood they are in, what kind of wine they typically like, and how much they want to spend and go from there. That’s often how I (a wine writer) order even when I know the list well. It takes 90 seconds and works a charm.

t137.text: And to sum up my entire argument in one sentence: We (professionals whose work involves stuff enjoyed during a meal) should care about drinks as much as food. It all goes together.

t138.text: I really should let this go but lastly I just want to point out that the wine list you posted is no more obscure than many restaurant menus. Discussion is necessary before making a decision. The result is (should be) a more informed and satisfied guest.pic.twitter.com/bSIEDU4fQu

t140.text: Well, the way you qualified your original statement was by saying that you’re a pro eater. So the first assumption was that pro eaters have minimal wine knowledge. In fact you’re now saying that’s not the case, it seems.

t141.text: OK, here are words you could have said: “The cheap Loire white” “The Riesling" “The Aligoté” “The Grand Cru“ “The Premier Cru” “An Alsatian wine.” Any of those would have gotten you a specific bottle. Whether you’d be happy with, sans further info, it is another story entirely.

t142.text: But... surely a seasoned restaurant diner/writer knows or can guess that Puligny-Montrachet is a place in Burgundy? Am I truly off the mark for thinking that? It’s one of the better known crus.
